      {
        "id": 4217868,
        "name": "larry schaffer",
        "username": "larry_schaffer",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/larry_schaffer/{size}/447_2.png",
        "created_at": "2023-12-08T07:06:53.255Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Gabe_Berk\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"307844\" data-full=\"true\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/gabe_berk/48/3134_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> Gabe_Berk:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Why any winemaker/winery would not use DIAM aside from price is astonishing. Such a superior closure.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>There are some that would argue that, even with their potential faults, wines under natural cork will develop \u2018differently\u2019 than under DIAM and, in fact, natural cork will \u2018add some characteristics\u2019 to the wine that DIAM does not.</p>\n<p>Still so much to learn and understand . . .</p>\n<p>Cheers</p>",
